caption: I remember the first time I saw a town full of rainbow flags -- Provincetown, Massachusetts, in the mid-90s. P-Town has long been a popular getaway for the LGBT community. There aren't even any gay bars in town (though there are Pride nights at some bars). It's just a rural small town that welcomes all with open arms, no matter who you are or who you love. Because that's the right thing to do. üåà Being an ally isn't just about not discriminating against LGBT people. caption: This is Bo-Kaap, the brightly painted Cape Malay neighborhood of Cape Town. I had high expectations for this Instagram-candy neighborhood, but I'll be honest -- Cape Town is a city where you have to be far more on your toes about safety than other cities. Literally every Capetonian I talk to warns about safety issues sometime in our conversation. While you can relax a bit in the V&A Waterfront area, you should be super-cautious everywhere else and not even go out at night on foot. And though I've been to Cape Town three times, even once solo, my intuition was pinging like crazy in Bo-Kaap, even in the middle of the day. Most locals warn you to be out of the neighborhood by 4:00 PM as that is when crime spikes, and even though @thebubblybeth and I visited around noon, I couldn't shake the feeling that we shouldn't be there. We took a few photos, talked to a handful of locals (some of whom stayed outside and watched out for us until we were off the street; all of whom told us to be careful with our cameras), then swiftly left the neighborhood. caption: You never forget the first time you see a #dolphin in the wild! One of the best places to see dolphins roam free in #Australia is #MonkeyMia in the #SharkBay region. Every morning, dolphins come to feed at the shore. Unlike most dolphin tourism activities, this is an event created with sustainability in mind.
